Summary

In this is a case study I will analyze data from FitBit users, which is a personal fitness tracker. The key objective is to gain insights from FitBit data to drive business decisions for another health tracker company Bellabeat. This insights can be applied to the Bellabeat products such as Leaf (tracker braclet) and Time (wellness watch) that connect to Bellabeat app. The app provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. The data and some instructions were provided by Google Data Analytics. The analysis was performed using R, and the script is provided at the end of this document (using same order of outputs).

The main aproach is to develop business task based on pre-determined questions, in order to reach the case study goal, which is esentially to provide Bellabeat with recommendations for their marketing strategy. The business task for this case study is to analyze FitBeat data to gain insights for Bellabeat products and answer the following questions:

  • How was the data collected
  • Are the data limitations?
  • How licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility are addressed?
  • What are some trends in smart device usage?
  • What insights can be gained from hourly and daily user activity data?
  • What are the sleep trends of the users?
  • Are there correlations between the variables that can help develope a better marketing strategy?
  • Are there trends between different groups of users.
  • How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Data Preparation

Data Summary:

There are 18 available datasets that were obtained from Kaggle(XXXX add link). The datasets are comprised of 33 unique users. The user data was tracked from 4/12/2016 to 5/12/2016 (over 30 days). Even though most of the dataset is based on automatic entries, some of values were entered manually, for example, for that of the weigth of the users. This fact resulted in some data limitations disscused in the next subsection.

The dates for the 18 datasets were recorded and some of them included hours, munutes and even second. The key columns include dates and times, calories burnt, steps, intensities, active minutes, hear rate, weigth; and some additional columns. The datasets are in both narrwo and wide format. Of the 18 datasets only XXXX were used, since some of the variables were repeated across the datasets and some of them were not important in the context of this case study.

Data Limitations:

I found that the data some limitations. First and foremost, the datasets have inputs of only 33 unique users. This tells us that the data is not comprehencive. In addition, of the 33 users not all of them entered the weight and sleep values. Here is the summary of the datasets and their unique user IDs:

We can see from the table that only 8 users entered the weigth information. This means that the data is incomplete and might not result in XXX.

Another limition that will most likely affect data integrity is that the data was only collected for 30 days. So, having only 33 users data 30 enty each will effect the reliability. Moreover we are ecpecting 30x33=990 rows, however, there are 940 in the daily dataset. This means that some users either did not enter the information, were not wearing the tracker or the app did not collect the data properly.

# merge the daily datasets
daily_data <- dailyActivity_merged %>%
  rename(ActivityDay = ActivityDate) %>% # rename to mathch with others
  left_join(dailyCalories_merged,by = c("Id", "ActivityDay")) %>%
  left_join(dailyIntensities_merged,by = c("Id", "ActivityDay")) %>%
  left_join(dailySteps_merged,by = c("Id", "ActivityDay")) %>%
  mutate(ActivityDay = mdy(ActivityDay), Day = weekdays(ActivityDay)) %>%
  rename(Date = ActivityDay) %>%
  select(Id,Date,Day, TotalSteps:VeryActiveDistance.y)


# merge the hourly datasets
hourly_data <- hourlyCalories_merged %>% 
  left_join(hourlyIntensities_merged, by = c("Id", "ActivityHour")) %>% 
  left_join(hourlySteps_merged, by = c("Id", "ActivityHour")) %>%
  mutate(ActivityHour = mdy_hms(ActivityHour)) %>%
  separate(ActivityHour,c("Date", "Time"), sep = " ") %>%
  mutate(Date = ymd(Date), Day = weekdays(Date)) %>%
  select(Id,Date,Day,Time:StepTotal)
 

# merge the narrow minute datasets
minute_data_narrow <- minuteCaloriesNarrow_merged %>%
  left_join(minuteIntensitiesNarrow_merged, by = c("Id", "ActivityMinute")) %>%
  left_join(minuteMETsNarrow_merged, by = c("Id", "ActivityMinute")) %>%
  left_join(minuteStepsNarrow_merged, by = c("Id", "ActivityMinute")) %>%
  mutate(ActivityMinute = mdy_hms(ActivityMinute)) %>%
  separate(ActivityMinute,c("Date", "Time"), sep = " ") %>%
  mutate(Date = ymd(Date), Day = weekdays(Date)) %>%
  select(Id,Date,Day,Time:Steps)

minute_data_hours <- minute_data_narrow %>%
  mutate(Time = as.POSIXct(hms::parse_hms(Time))) %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  summarise(average_calories = mean(Calories),
            average_steps = mean(Steps))
